Pravdameer helps to lay the trap. *RP*<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
*ooc* Let me state at the outset that what I am about to describe is for RP purposes only and is how Prav, ICly, saw the events of the Solus Raid on Befallen. I will state for the record that the 3 people I grouped with were fantastic, and i wish I had been able to stay longer, but RL had the nerve to step in and deny me such pleasures. In any event, on with the tale...<br>
<br>
EDIT: Posted to Vault Network and VH, OED, and House W'Rath boards RP Area.<br>
<br>
======================================<br>
<br>
Pravdameer had struggled hard since his fall to the likes of the rogue Lythe. He understood how to bide his time and build his resources. Many of those he sought vengeance upon had departed from the lands, or faded into retirement - but still there were some left to whom he owed a debt or two.<br>
<br>
As a result, when he was approached by others about one such &quot;happy couple&quot; (he couldn’t help but chuckle at the irony), he lept at the opportunity. He made the sacrifice, and descended into the bowels of Befallen amongst several of the unbelievers. The task given him, by those in charge of this foolish escapade, was to heal those within his group. He wasn’t even given the courtesy of being grouped with members of the Chosen Race - he was forced to work with a half-breed off-key bard from the group associating themselves with the traitor lokus by the name of Aaranos, a human of the lowest of classes named Quezex (he was one of those who claimed to be a &quot;Holy Warrior&quot; or what some fools called Paladins) who was from that group he had crossed paths with before named the Order of Elder Dragons, and some little ankle biter of a gnome named Jezzeth who seemed to be an enchanter who couldn't keep a single creature pacified (he was constantly blaming his failures on others within the group).<br>
<br>
Once the foursome descended into the depths, they seemed to be on their own, and Pravdameer did his best to at least _appear_ to be helping. In all actuality, he simply was waiting for just the right moment. For Atoxus had told him that She would be at this raid. He told the young Prophet that although his last creation had departed the lands for a time, there was still something of it's ilk inside of her, and this could be put to use.<br>
<br>
When the time was right, at Atoxus's command, Pravdameer departed from his body and sped up to the entrance to the caves where he had bound his spirit. (*ooc* Yes, the healer screwed up and bit the big one and died *mutter* I feel so stupid some times. *chuckle*). He searched carefully while awaiting his group members to open the doors to down below, and finally found her. While nobody else was around, Atoxus restrained her so Pravdameer would not be attacked. The young prophet then looked at her and said, &quot;I know you for what you are, creature - and I offer a proposition.&quot; When the beast seemed to offer no response other than a snarl, the young prophet laid out his plan. The beast then smiled a cold sadistic grin as she cackled with unreserved glee and removed the wedding ring from the finger of it's host and handed it to the priest. &quot;Be sure he gets his gift as soon as possible,&quot; she said before rending her way back into the bowels of befallen. Soon after, the Prophet found an excuse to be done with these fools, and left the lightdwellers to their fate.<br>
<br>
At Atoxus's direction, he headed for Freeport. For there, Atoxus told him, was the woman he would need. As he went, he changed his garments and became what many in Freeport seemed to know him as - the wandering tier'dal tradesman who seemed alright. After some work for the town, he had managed to be somewhat accepted - even if only with a degree of apprehension. At least now he could do business in this fould wretched city and not cause too much commotion. He hated having to soil himself so, but then that was probably why Atoxus insisted upon it.<br>
<br>
He arrived in Freeport, and went down the alleys until he came upon the young wood elf lass Atoxus had told him would be there. She was perfect - just the right skin color and size - she even had the look of a ranger to her. He stopped the young woman and said, &quot;Excuse me, but would you try this ring on? My bride to be is just about your size, and I want to be sure that it fits.&quot; Somewhat suspiscious still, the young girl was finally enticed by the bag of platinum that dark elf held out to her. &quot;You can have this if you'll just place the ring on your finger my dear.&quot; As the girl placed the ring on, and Pravdameer saw it was a proper fit he nodded his head, and then handed the bag to the girl with one hand, and brought his mace around with the other and smashed in her skull. He then quickly grabbed the skinning knife out of his pack and neatly severed the finger with the ring still on it. &quot;Yes my dear, and I guess you won't be needing this anymore either,&quot; he said as he grabbed his bag of coins. He quickly hurried off as Atoxus warned him of approaching guards, and hurried back to the safety of Nektulos.<br>
<br>
As he arrived safely back at his new home, he smiled with anticipation. He called for his guildmate Xareth, and gave him the finger with the ring still on it. Xareth smiled with sadistic glee as the young Prophet laid out his plans, then nodded once and was off to deliver the message. &quot;Ah yes, my friend,&quot; Pravdameer said to Atoxus. &quot;It won't be long now before we have a new guest in the dungeons. I wonder if this rogue will be as much fun as the one named Lythe was?&quot; <br>
