-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Xareth made his way through the Erudite city, once again locked in the foul body of the young bard he so hated. It was a disgusting feeling, to use this curse in such a manner, but it would work well for the purpose. The rogue he sought, Minz, was somewhere in the forest outside of Erudin, waiting for his guildmate, Silverstarr, to appear. Well, he would soon learn the truth. <br>
<br>
The false bard ran to the edge of the city to the Toxxulia Forest and waited for the half elf to make his appearance. Before long, he did, and Xareth approached nonchalantly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hail, light brother. How goes your hunt?&quot; He saw Minz raise an eyebrow at him and resisted the urge to run him through with his sword right then and there. Best to wait, to make him suffer. <br>
<br>
Minz shrugged. &quot;I'm fine, Sil. You feeling alright? You seem a little different.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Why, I feel fine. I merely had something of value to give you.&quot; Xareth eyed the large pike the rogue was sporting. A new weapon, probably poisonous. He made a mental note of it for future notice<br>
<br>
The rogue's eyes lit up and he stepped forward. Xareth involuntarily stepped back a pace and held out a hand. &quot;Patience. A moment, I will show you…&quot; He grinned wickedly and reached for the small black pouch he'd retrieved earlier. He loosened the strings and opened the bag, not letting the rogue, who was hopping around him and trying to peek, see its contents. His mall Wood Elven hand (*spit*) closed around the lone item and pulled it free of the bag.<br>
<br>
&quot;Here, rogue. I think you should find this an item of interest.&quot; Chuckling coldly, he handed the finger with Orrianna's ring on it to Minz and stepped back. <br>
<br>
Minz stared at it for a moment, frozen with horror. &quot;What… what is this??!!&quot; <br>
<br>
Xareth, no longer posing as the bard, grinned and retreated back a few paces, putting space between them. &quot;What is the matter, elf? Don't recognize your own wife's ring?&quot; <br>
<br>
The rogue roared and launched himself at Xareth, dropping both the finger and his pike. Xareth saw it coming and kicked into reverse, but the bard's body responded too slowly and he wound up on the ground, with a very irate rogue pinning him. &quot;YOU! What have you done! Where is Silver?? Where is MY WIFE!!&quot; <br>
<br>
Xareth regarded him cooly, enjoying the other's hatred and pain. He knew that the rogue would not seriously injure him while he was in control of Silverstarr's body. No, Minz would never do that to his friend. Xareth let the enraged rogue shake him roughly for a minute, and wondered how far Minz would go to get his answers. Would he actually hurt him in Silver's body? He considered that for a minute. It would most definitely ride heavily on the half elf's mind later if he did. No, best not try this time. He needed to get the rogue to go to Nektulos.<br>
<br>
The false bard shoved Minz off him and stood. Minz was panting now, breathless from shouting obscenities and demands. His face was flushed almost purple, and Xareth could see pure rage burning in his eyes. Good. &quot;Are you ready to listen, lightdweller? Or shall I just leave and allow your wife to die at the hands of our priest, Pravdameer?&quot; The rogue reacted to Pravdameer's name and started for him again. Xareth shot a hand up in warning. &quot;Careful, light one. I will tell you this: we have Orrianna. If you want to see her alive again, and in respectively good health, seek Pravdameer and I in the Lavastorm Mountains. But be wary… you come alone. Try to trick us, and she will die. Quite painfully, I might add.&quot; <br>
<br>
Minz glared death at him. &quot;How DARE you… I will have your head for this Xareth, I swear it. You and Pravdameer both.&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
The false bard stared at him in mock shock. &quot;Oh? We shall see, light one. I suggest you hurry.&quot; He retreated into the shadows of the forest, chuckling evilly. Minz glared, his eyes promising death. On an impulse, Xareth stopped, still within Minz's sight, and let Silverstarr collapse to the ground. <br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
He returned to his own self a short while later. His whole body hurt, and fatigue had set into his mind. He needed rest, but that could wait until he reported to Pravdameer. He stood stiffly and stretched. Prav would want to know quickly, so that the trap might be set up before the rogue made his way across the continent to them. <br>
<br>
Xareth set out for where he knew the Priest would be, and looked forward to the fun that lay ahead.<br>
