<br>
The damned cats had really taken it out on him. He and Silver could have easily defeated the onslaught of feline ferocity. Worse yet, the four cats that were now focusing all there loving attention on him, stood between him and the door!<br>
<br>
&quot;SILVER!!&quot; He yelled.<br>
<br>
His only answer was a fierce slash of claws across his face.<br>
<br>
Jabbing hard with his harpoon, Minz drove the noxious piece of fur back. Feinting to his right, he drew the cats off balance, forcing them to over extend their slashing attacks. Creating an easy opening for him to dive under. But he hit the earth to hard, twisting his wrist. <br>
<br>
?DAMN!!? He yelled inwardly. 'How in the hell do you expect to roll holding a 5 foot spear!!?? IDDIO . . . ' But the claws in his back cut his self-chastisment short. His training kicked into action automatically. 'ROGUE ESCAPE PLAN NUMBER 324' His practice and study?s were paying off. Without even thinking about it, his mind analyzed the situation and put forth his best and only option.<br>
<br>
Pulling his feet underneath him, he launched himself into a sprint for the exit. Flailing his arms above his head, screaming at the top of his lungs. <br>
<br>
&quot;AAAAAHHHHHHHHHHH!!!&quot;<br>
<br>
============================<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll have your head Xareth!!!&quot; Minz shouted into the woods.<br>
<br>
Feathered wings fluttered, startled at the harsh voice crashing through the serene atmosphere of the Toxx Forrest.<br>
<br>
He willed his legs to move, but the couldn't. He felt weak and leaden. A shock of chill seemed to wrap around him. &quot;Nnnooo,&quot; he whispered. Dropping to his knees. &quot;Please no.&quot; Silver, or Xareth, as she had called herself, was gone. Melting into the woods.<br>
<br>
Looking down her beheld with horror the disembodied finger. Soft and delicate. Slender, belying its . . . her strength. His stomach churned as he imagined it being wrenched from her body. It was no clean cut. Nooo that would have been a mercy. But torn, ripped from her hand. <br>
<br>
Tendons stretched<br>
<br>
Skin torn <br>
<br>
Veins and artteries ripped in two<br>
<br>
Minz shuddered. He'd seen far worse gore. But none had ever shaken him soo deeply. Tentatively he reached for it, shying away form touching the lost digit. Sighing heavily, the rogue placed his harpoon atop the finger, and pried the ring off with his stiletto. Trying, unsuccessfully to leave the fair skin of the lost finger unmarred.<br>
<br>
Holding it in his hands, he relived the moment of his proposal. The were stalking bandits in the Karanas. The moon was high in the sky, and they were resting. Orrianna sat against a tall tree, while he was lying on his side, stretched out on the earth . . .<br>
<br>
=================================<br>
<br>
Nervously, Minz twisted the ring on his pinky with his thumb. It was a small thin band of gold with a fine gem set in it. So small was the ring that it would not pass his second knuckle.<br>
<br>
Nothing too fancy. He had stolen grander rings. No, not too fancy at all.<br>
<br>
This ring he had actually bought.<br>
<br>
It was far too small on even his nimble elven fingers. The ring was clearly meant for the hand of a lady. And he had a particular lady in mind.<br>
<br>
Orri, more than anyone else, had helped him find himself again. Her unrelenting care. She had tended his wounds when they needed it and kicked him in the butt as well. As his feelings grew for her, he could feel the sanguine fury shough away from him. Like a snake shedding its skin.<br>
<br>
There were many hands that pulled him from the deep end of his soul, but few that had touched him so deeply. Whether she knew it. 'Gods I hope that she does know,' Minz thought. They had declared their love for eachother. They had shared their passion, their hurt and their shame. But neither would or could yield. The flame of their hearts pulled them together like nothing he had ever felt. And now they sat here. On his farm, under the night sky.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are so beautiful,&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
Orri blushed. She was still not completely comfortable with his affections. But she pushed him away no more. Her glares had become less vehement when he called her &quot;Lady.&quot; And she let him help her. All of this brought more joy to his heart then he could put into words. 'Is it too soon?' he thought. 'Am I moving too fast? We are both so young. Not that young though.' He had argued with himself for quite some time now.<br>
<br>
The two sat in silence a while longer. Holding eachothers hands. Watching the breeze chase the clouds across the night sky.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am trying to think of a last name Minz,&quot; Orri said. It was a common practice for denizens of Norrath to take new surnames as the entered adulthood. Not universal, but common enough. Orri stared up at the clouds, lost in her ponderings.<br>
<br>
'HELL!' though Minz. 'Now or never!' &quot;I know a good one,&quot; he said<br>
<br>
&quot;Hmmm?&quot; Orrianna replied, still lost in thought.<br>
<br>
&quot;Elandril,&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
The name pulled her out of her musings, and she looked at him quizzically. &quot;Elandril?&quot; she asked, not connecting the name to Minz.<br>
<br>
Scooting closer to her, Minz said simply, &quot;It's my family name.&quot;<br>
<br>
Recognition of what Minz was saying lit Orri's face like the sun rising over the plains. The color drained out of her face, and her eyes grew a bit wider. Minz slipped the glove off his left hand and pulled the slim engagement band free of his pinky. Orri seemed to will speech, but no words fell from her lips. Taking her hand, he put the ring on her slender finger. &quot;Marry me Orrianna, and I'll spend the rest of my days trying to make you happy.&quot;<br>
<br>
He drifted back out of his memories, only to find his face wet with tears. &quot;Lavastrom.&quot; He muttered as he set out to look for the wizards spires and his wife.<br>
<br>
Minz Elandril<br>
Pendragon to the Order of the Elder Dragons<br>
&quot;Orri! I have to give her back the wallet AND the money?&quot;<br>
